<p><b>Thomas Hobbes</b> (5 April 1588 – 4 December 1679) was an <a href="/wiki/English_(people)" title="English (people)" class="mw-redirect">English</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosopher</a>, remembered today for his work on <a href="/wiki/Political_philosophy" title="Political philosophy">political philosophy</a>. His 1651 book <i><a href="/wiki/Leviathan_(book)" title="Leviathan (book)">Leviathan</a></i> established the foundation for most of Western political philosophy from the perspective of <a href="/wiki/Social_contract" title="Social contract">social contract</a> theory.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Hobbes also contributed to a diverse array of fields, including <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a>, <a href="/wiki/Geometry" title="Geometry">geometry</a>, physics of <a href="/wiki/Gas" title="Gas">gases</a>, <a href="/wiki/Theology" title="Theology">theology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</a>, general <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Political_science" title="Political science">political science</a>. His account of human nature as self-interested cooperation has proved to be an enduring theory in the field of <a href="/wiki/Philosophical_anthropology" title="Philosophical anthropology">philosophical anthropology</a>.</p>
