<p><a name="In_popular_culture" id="In_popular_culture"></a></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline">In popular culture</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hobbes_(Calvin_and_Hobbes)" title="Hobbes (Calvin and Hobbes)">Hobbes</a>, the tiger in <a href="/wiki/Bill_Watterson" title="Bill Watterson">Bill Watterson</a>'s comic strip <i><a href="/wiki/Calvin_and_Hobbes" title="Calvin and Hobbes">Calvin and Hobbes</a></i>, was named after Thomas Hobbes, while his companion <a href="/wiki/Calvin_(Calvin_and_Hobbes_character)" title="Calvin (Calvin and Hobbes character)" class="mw-redirect">Calvin</a> was named after the <a href="/wiki/Protestant_Reformation" title="Protestant Reformation">Reformation</a> theologian <a href="/wiki/John_Calvin" title="John Calvin">John Calvin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13" title=""><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Monty_Python" title="Monty Python">Monty Python</a> mentions Hobbes as being "fond of his dram" in <a href="/wiki/Bruces%27_Philosophers_Song" title="Bruces' Philosophers Song">Bruces' Philosophers Song</a>.</li>
</ul>
